In the days of the wild west, there was a young cowboy who wanted more than anything to be the fastest gunfighter in the world.

He practiced every minute of his spare time, but he knew that he wasn't yet first-rate and that there must be something he was doing wrong.

Sitting in a saloon one Saturday night, he recognized an elderly man seated at the bar who had the reputation of being a fast gun in his day.

The young gunslinger took a seat next to the old-timer, bought him a drink, and told him the story of his great ambition. "Do you think you could give me some tips?" he asked.

The old man looked him up and down and said, "Well, how fast are you?"

The young man drew his pistol pretty quick and before anyone knew it, then shoots the hat off of the piano player's head!"

The old man looks over at the piano player and says to the young man, "Well, that wasn't bad. But you're wearing your gun too high. You should have your holster lower on your leg so you can get to your gun quicker when you draw. And son, tie the holster down on your leg."

The young man did as he was told, stood up, whipped out his Colt Peacemaker and shot the tie off the piano player.

"That's terrific!" said the young gunslinger. "Got any more tips for me?"

"Yup," said the old man. "Cut a notch out of your holster where the hammer hits it. That'll give you a smoother draw."

"Will that make me faster?" asked the younger man. "You bet it will," said the old-timer.

The young man took out his knife, cut the notch, stood up, drew his gun in a blur, then shot a cuff link off the piano player.

"Wow!" said the young gunslinger. "I'm learning' somethin' here. Got any more tips?"

The old man pointed to a large can in a corner of the saloon. "See that axle grease over there? Coat your gun with it. Just but the gun in it, layer it with grease! "

The young man went over to the can and smeared some of the grease on the barrel of his gun.

"No," said the old-time, "I mean smear it all over the gun, handle and all."

"Will that make me a faster gunfighter?" asked the young man.

"Probably not!" said the old-timer, "But when Doc Holliday gets done playing that song on the piano, that grease will make it hurt less when he shoves that gun up your ass!"

The Last Ride

"Congratulations! You can now handle this route on your own. Remember the company's protocol", Bobbie beamed as he finished assessing Dave's performance for Bus Service 13. "Enjoy the night events following the route", Bobbie mischievously hinted at Dave, his junior who had just joined the company. Today, Dave steeled his nerves. He will be on his own, handling the midnight "last bus" schedule for Service 13, a long but important service, as it serviced a massive industrial area. Of course it's a bustling service in the day, with workers to and fro. As part of regulation, the company has to operate the service even till midnight where there's usually no passengers. Oddly, his only assignment will be to drive this service at this timing, and nothing else. Noone else in the company was jealous of his work but Dave cast aside those thoughts. Satisfied with the initial inspection of the double-decker bus, he started on his journey from the depot. With only the scenes of forest edges flying by, he examined quiet roads and empty pathways but an eerie feeling crept up as he passed a dilapidated graveyard. The government planned to exhume the site to pave way for more industrial projects, or at least that was what he had read in the papers. Approaching the start of the industrial area, he wondered if there'll be anyone boarding the bus. As expected, there was noone in the multitude of bus-stops he passed. As the last few factories loomed before him, he noticed someone at a bus-stop. It was an old lady, dressed simply in a white dress, her dishevelled hair blocking her face, but two things were apparent. She held out her hand flagging the bus but her eyes were transfixed on something above. Specifically, the upper deck of the bus. Dave slowed down, feeling slightly nervous and as he approaches, the figure maintained her position but her gaze never strayed. Confident that the person was physically there, he stopped and the woman boarded, her face distraught. "I have never seen so many people up there at this time, it must be because today's Friday the 13th", she shivered. Dave was dumbfounded as she took her seat beside the stairwell leading to the upper deck. Indeed today was Friday 13th as he eyed the woman through the rear view mirror. She was 5 seats away from him but her fear was contagious. Dave had goosebumps as he pulled off. "I'm sorry madam, but what do you mean people up there? You're the first passenger", Dave inquired, trying to quench his curiousity. "Nothing nothing! I can hear them stomping above as though they're trying to shush me", the woman squeaked as she clasped her hand in prayer. Dave was mortified. He kept looking at the CCTV monitor panel but there was noone in the upper decks. His fear was somewhat relieved as they entered the residential zone and 13 stops later, the woman buzzed the stop. Dave couldn't believe his eyes when the woman ran fleeing out of the bus at her stop. Her face displayed pure agony as she turned back for the last time to look at the bus before disappearing into the shadows of the houses. Dave controlled his breathing and continued driving. It was only a few stops away till the final depot, so he must see this journey to the end. Still, he kept peeking at the CCTV monitors to be sure but nothing happened as he ended his work for the day. Dave didn't tell anyone what happened as he turned up for work the next day. Perhaps it was an anomaly, there was no point in looking like a mad man after just a day's work. He checked the bus and headed out for the journey. The same start as yesterday and again at the same stop, there appeared the lady again. She looked the same, save for her change of clothes but still her gaze was transfixed on the upper deck. "Today's less busy... but there's a hulking presence amongst them", she whispered as she sat further way from Dave, nearer the exit doors. Chill went down his spine. Was there a murderous intent above that he didn't notice? He scanned the monitors just to be safe but he couldn't see anything. Even Dave who didn't believe in the supernatural, was starting to question his beliefs, as he noticed the woman sobbing in her seat. As if a replay of last night's activities, the woman sprung out and ran when they reached her stop. She didn't even look back. These series of events repeated themselves as Dave drove the service for more than a year. He thought he could get used to it but he just couldn't. Different nights, different terrors. It has gotten to the point that the woman now regularly sat on the exit door steps, clutching to the walls, sniffling her cries. "There's something on the roof", "I can hear them trying to go down the stairwells", "Stop looking into the upper deck, they're restless", "We're damned in this service", "I hope you're praying as hard as me, it's the only way to resist", "Stop crying and wailing, stop! Stop, I can't help you!!!", "God bless me please!", all manners of horrified speeches were said by the woman, either directed to him or to the dwelling above. "I pray you are safe!", "God bless your soul", "Be safe", sometimes she would say that to Dave before she alighted. Dave hated it when she said parting words because it hinted a terrifying presence. And then one day it stopped. The lady stopped appearing. The same day the government had also begun exhuming the sites and transferring the remains to another mortuary. Dave rue the day he started noticing her absence. She was the only company he had in this damned service route. He kept checking the CCTV above, afraid of the unknown. He started praying from the moment he start the journey. He brought books of faith, talisman, charms and even turned to vegetarian diet to rid himself of bad karma. But whatever he did, the pressure behind him grew and grew. Without the woman, things had started to go awry. He didn't notice them at first but he thought he could start seeing the negativities himself. Flickers in the CCTV monitor, he felt the temperature drop, opposing cars high beamed him, and it started to affect his driving. He would narrowly avoid collision with structures while checking the monitors. He would unconciously speed up and beat red lights when in the vicinity of the violated graveyard. 2 months of this has taken a toll on Dave. He had nightmares every night, images of dark shadows consuming the interior of the bus. In just the short period, Dave had lost a lot of weight, he looked gaunt and his eyes lifeless. His concerned wife pulled him aside and just said she loved him, their children loved him, and if work was the reason he had become like this, he should find another job. Dave spent the morning thinking about this. The job paid well since it was night hours, it was only 1 route and he had never fell ill in the past year, despite his horror experiences. It was only after the lady disappeared that things have taken a physical toll on him. He concluded that she was part of his divine protection. He had made up his mind. He will tender his resignation. In front of his superiors, Dave explained his reasons for quitting. He didn't care if they didn't believed him, and he even turned down their offer for a raise. They must know something, that must be why they want to keep me. Without anyone else wanting to run the midnight bus service 13, the company could face a legal repercussion. In the end, they had to call back Bobbie, the only person who had drove that route before Dave. In fact, Bobbie drove exclusively that route for more than a decade, never taking a day off. Dave took his leave and lo and behold, he met Bobbie outside the office. Bobbie exlaimed his surprise, "I heard you're resigning? But why?" "I couldn't continue working that route after the only passenger, this lady, I don't know anything about her, but after she stopped apeparing, I just don't have the will to continue", Dave said. "That's... a damn shame! She was the only reason why I had agreed to come back! My ailing eyesight was why the company transferred me to day shift. But if I had a choice, I would have stayed on service 13! But now that she's gone... it's all over", Bobbie wept. Bobbie continued hopelessly, "Now who's gonna accompany me in that night ride...". "I understand what you meant Bobbie. In hindsight, she was also the reason why I stayed. She was my protector, my guardian angel", Dave sighed. "What the fuck are you talking about?", quizzed Bobbie suddenly. Dave told his stories to a bewildered Bobbie, who kept quiet the whole time. "That foxy vixen... I guess she must have retired from her company" mumbled Bobbie. Noticing the shocked look plastered on Dave's face. Bobbie chuckled, "I guess she'll really do anything to avoid paying the bus fare".

A judge was interviewing a woman regarding her pending divorce, and asked, "What are the grounds for your divorce?" She replied, "About four acres and a nice little home in the middle of the property with a stream running by." "No," he said, "I mean what is the foundation of this case?" "It is made of concrete, brick and mortar," she responded. "I mean," he continued, "What are your relations like?" "I have an aunt and uncle living here in town, and so do my husband's parents." He said, "Do you have a real grudge?" "No," she replied, "We have a two-car carport and have never really needed one." "Please," he tried again, "is there any infidelity in your marriage?" "Yes, both my son and daughter have stereo sets. We don't necessarily like the music, but the answer to your questions is yes." "Ma'am, does your husband ever beat you up?" "Yes," she responded, "about twice a week he gets up earlier than I do." Finally, in frustration, the judge asked, "Lady, why do you want a divorce?" "Oh, I don't want a divorce," she replied. "I've never wanted a divorce. My husband does. He said he can't communicate with me!"

What do you get for attempting human cloning with a drummer?

As I type this, I am slowly dying of cancer. This is my story, and I hope whoever reads this takes this as a warning.

I was never one of the cool kids. Ever since I was born I have been, if no better way to put it, average. My mother used to tell me the story of when I was born. Apparently, when I first popped out, I didn't cry, as one would expect a newborn baby to. I simply peered around a bit as the nurses rushed over to take care of me. How's that "average"? I don't know. It's just a story my mom used to tell me, and I think it sets the stage rather well for what was to come. The days of my innocence flew by, and soon I was about to enter 9th grade. That was when my dad was posted to a new state by his company. Leaving behind my home of nearly 14 years, I stepped into the brave new world of Mississippi. Of course, that meant I enrolled in a new high school. There, lost and alone, I stumbled around until I met my two guys who would become the best friends I would ever have. To cut a long story short, I got to know them in math class. Bored by a particularly dry lecture (something about calculus) we struck a conversation and found that we shared a common interest: We were all crazy into gaming. We talked about the newest Metal Gear, and it all went uphill from there. Their names were Luke and Missile. Luke was a bit of a nerd, but an all-round cool guy, and an amazing friend. If you were in a jam, you could be sure Luke would be there to see you through. Missile, on the other hand, was a wild one; always on the move, and with such an excited and bubbly manner of speaking you could feel yourself getting carried along as he spoke. At first, I thought he was Latino, but turns out he was half-filipino. Oh, and his real name was Gonzales. He just liked being called "Missile" (for whatever reason, I do not know. I doubt even he himself really does). So it was with these two that I spent a happy 6 months in high school. My parents seemed to be happy that I was coping well. We lived in a good neighborhood, and our next-door neighbor, a German fellow by the name of Mr Anderson who always wore sunglasses and had a pot belly, would often invite us over for barbecues and such. Luke and Missile would join in on occasion, and we would talk about life, school, and anything really, before popping in Mario Party in Mr Anderson's Wii and playing to our heart's content. Life was going pretty well. Then, I met her. Her name was Trucy, and I will forever remember the day I first laid my eyes on her. It was in art class, and amidst the smell of stale paint and canvas I caught a whiff of perfume. I looked up, and there she was. Beautiful brown curls framed her perfect, blue-eyed face. And that smile. Oh god. I swear I collaped into a dreamy, unmanly heap on the table for the entire lesson which followed. When I met up with Luke and Missile in the cafeteria, my thoughts still dwelled on her. Luke must have sensed that something was going on, because he waved his hand in front of me, saying "Earth to Arlon, Earth to Arlon, Arlon do you copy", which snapped me out of my trance-like state. "What's with you man?" he asked. "You're not your usual self today." "Oh, Nothing." I lied. But, of course, they found out eventually. And they were really cool about it. Turns out, Missile knew Trucy from Economics, so with that in mind, we started to brainstorm ideas on how to approach her. Luke suggested we take it slow. "What about you 'invite' us all to the movies, Missile?" he said. "We'll book tickets, then get trucy next to Arlon. We can work it out from there." We did exactly that, and it turned out pretty well. Better, in fact, than I expected -- we managed to exchange phone numbers. Missile and Luke congratulated me on a job well done, then we went to get Taco Bell. There, we planned our next course of action. Over the next few weeks, Trucy and I got to know each other, whether through phone calls or the clandestine operations Luke and Missile helped me arrange. Soon, I didn't need their help anymore, and we went on our first date together at a park (yes, very creative I know). It was then that I knew I had to tell her. "Trucy?" "Yes Arlon?" "There's something... i need to tell you." "What is it?" I hesitated. Then, I saw them. Sitting on a bench reading newspapers. Cheeky bastards, turns out they had arranged this too? Luke smiled and gave me a thumbs-up while Missile mouthed "Just do it." So I did it. "I... I kinda like you, hehe" (it probably sounded even more awkward than it does here) "Oh, Arlon" And we shared our first kiss. I was in heaven. My heaven would last through the three years we dated. Then, just when I thought our relationship was truly budding, we broke up. Yes, it was that abrupt. Trucy loved someone else now, and I was left behind. The feeling in my chest that I experienced that day, cannot be described in words. Suffice to say, I was devastated, heartbroken. I went home the day she broke up with me without speaking a word to anyone. When I got home, I shut the door and tried to rationalise with myself. "It's ok Arlon. You'll manage. There are plenty other girls out there" "Don't be sad Arlon. it was not meant to be." But the more I thought about it, the worse I felt. Over the next few days, Luke and Missile tried to talk me out of it, tried to make me forget it, get it over with. But it did not help. I slipped further and further into depression. Yes, I started hanging out late and doing drugs. Yes, I started doing alcohol. I went from respectable, generally nice guy to a coke-snorting, chain-smoking hobo. But through all this, Luke and Missile stood by me. Shame on me that I didn't appreciate them then. I remember once, I, in a drunken stupor, smashed a bottle and used it to stab Missile, who was trying to stop me from drinking so much ( and probably get alcohol poisoning). That was the end of it between me and Missile. I tried committing suicide once. I climbed to the top of the roof and jumped down. I got caught in some tree branches and ended up on the ground with only a gash across my leg. I cursed the heavens loudly for letting me survive. Mr Anderson, alerted by the noise, quickly brought me in and wrapped up my wound. I sobbed as he picked up the phone to dial my parents, who were at work. A year later, I saw Trucy outside a bar with her new boyfriend. I couldn't control myself and rushed up to them. "YOU RUINED MY LIFE!" The two of them were taken by surprise and the boyfriend raised his fist. "YOU TOOK HER FROM ME" I yelled. "YOU TOOK MY LIFE FROM ME!" and I swung wildly at him. Suddenly, there was an excruciating pain in my abdomen. I screamed, then I collapsed. Next thing I remember seeing was the cold, sterile hospital ceiling. I awoke to find Luke, Trucy and my parents by my side, her boyfriend leaning against the wall. The doctor came in, and revealed to me that I had a tumor in my liver. I started to cry. I had wasted my life, all my potential, over one stupid breakup. Why did I start doing drugs? Why did I start doing alcohol? "It should be okay," the doctor said. "But we'll need to monitor it for a while to look for any unusual developments. Rest now, ok?" My tears turned into those of joy. It was like being born again. I had a second chance. It was time to turn over a new leaf. At the advice of Mr Anderson, my parents put aside their pride and hired a professional counsellor to guide me through the tough times. I also had to take antidepressants. But I was getting better. Trucy agreed that she had handled the breakup badly, and we promised to keep in touch, if only just as friends. I would laze in the couch feeling a little blue. Today, I was feeling it a little more than usual. I started playing Metal Gear Soild V half-heartedly to take my mind off it, when the doorbell rang. It was Luke. "Came to visit," he said. "How are things?" "Oh, they're alright." We chatted for a while. Then he said. "Cheer up, old sport. Here, have a look at this, figured you would find it funny." He whipped out his iPhone 6 and opened up 4chan. And that's how I got cancer.

By the time he's able to receive visitors, the man is desperate to talk to his antivax friends, to let them know the vital truth he brought back from the other side.
